00:00:14.100 --> 00:00:15.240
LUCINDA SANDERS: Sit With
Me is based around

00:00:15.240 --> 00:00:16.670
an iconic red chair.

00:00:16.670 --> 00:00:20.220
And there's so many things that
a chair really embodies.

00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:22.880
It's about sitting for the
future of technology.

00:00:22.880 --> 00:00:25.760
It's about not standing for
anything less than women's

00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:27.640
full participation
in computing.

00:00:27.640 --> 00:00:29.750
And I hope this campaign
really helps

00:00:29.750 --> 00:00:31.190
us understand that.

00:00:31.190 --> 00:00:32.920
We need more women
in the workforce.

00:00:32.920 --> 00:00:33.865
We need their creativity.

00:00:33.865 --> 00:00:35.390
We need their skills.

00:00:35.390 --> 00:00:36.960
ALAN McCONNELL: We've learned
over time that you can't build

00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:38.860
great products if you don't have
a team that empathizes

00:00:38.860 --> 00:00:40.752
with and understands
the audience that

00:00:40.752 --> 00:00:42.040
the product is for.

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:43.530
LUCINDA SANDERS: We're doing
the Sit With Me campaign

00:00:43.530 --> 00:00:46.690
because we want the world to
know that women are great

00:00:46.690 --> 00:00:48.040
technical thinkers.

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:49.820
And it's time to do it now.

00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:52.280
MATTHEW McTEE: I think the world
needs a campaign like

00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:55.773
Sit With Me in order to ignite
a commitment towards really

00:00:55.773 --> 00:00:59.270
driving more women into
careers in technology.

00:00:59.270 --> 00:01:01.200
SHERYL SANDBERG: You know the
women who are dedicated in

00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:03.450
computer science, who go into
math, who go into other

00:01:03.450 --> 00:01:05.980
technical areas,
they're great.

00:01:05.980 --> 00:01:08.190
And it starts with believing
they can do it.

00:01:08.190 --> 00:01:10.730
COLLEEN BLAKE: As a mother, I
want to break the stereotype

00:01:10.730 --> 00:01:12.800
to show my daughters that
hey, you can go to

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:13.930
that engineering class.

00:01:13.930 --> 00:01:16.620
So it's part of telling that
story that's important for me.

00:01:16.620 --> 00:01:19.240
LUCINDA SANDERS: We want women
helping to solve the problems

00:01:19.240 --> 00:01:20.430
that the world faces.

00:01:20.430 --> 00:01:22.100
That's what we hope
this campaign

00:01:22.100 --> 00:01:23.490
provides a catalyst for.

00:01:23.490 --> 00:01:26.370
JESSICA MURILLO: We sent out
an email a couple weeks ago

00:01:26.370 --> 00:01:28.950
about our International Women's
Day event and wouldn't

00:01:28.950 --> 00:01:30.840
it be a great idea to
have this red chair?

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:33.430
LEAH BRUNSON: The campaign is
getting lots of great buzz

00:01:33.430 --> 00:01:34.450
here at Microsoft.

00:01:34.450 --> 00:01:37.950
We had about 100 people here
to talk about the powerful

00:01:37.950 --> 00:01:39.690
contributions of
women in tech.

00:01:39.690 --> 00:01:40.640
They want to hear more.

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:41.850
They want to get involved.

00:01:41.850 --> 00:01:45.620
We want you to have a Sit With
Me event or host a photo shoot

00:01:45.620 --> 00:01:49.030
or use the chair as an
award program or

00:01:49.030 --> 00:01:50.750
have a stealth campaign.

00:01:50.750 --> 00:01:51.510
JESSICA MURILLO: Just do it.

00:01:51.510 --> 00:01:52.780
It's not hard.

00:01:52.780 --> 00:01:54.310
You can request a red chair.

00:01:54.310 --> 00:01:55.590
You get some people together.

00:01:55.590 --> 00:01:56.530
You take some pictures.

00:01:56.530 --> 00:01:57.550
And you upload at the site.

00:01:57.550 --> 00:01:58.690
It's just easy.

00:01:58.690 --> 00:02:00.410
