00:10:57.280 --> 00:10:58.980
Because I was, like, well,
I'm a marketing manager.

00:10:58.980 --> 00:10:59.710
I just graduated.

00:10:59.710 --> 00:11:00.560
I have my MBA.

00:11:00.560 --> 00:11:01.920
And they said, well,
we're going to

00:11:01.920 --> 00:11:03.140
hire a VP of Marketing.

00:11:03.140 --> 00:11:05.720
And you'll report to that
VP of Marketing.

00:11:05.720 --> 00:11:08.170
And I waited and I waited.

00:11:08.170 --> 00:11:14.160
I waited for years for the VP
of Marketing until I learned

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:17.550
that I wasn't going to have a
person coming and telling me

00:11:17.550 --> 00:11:19.830
what to do, that I just had to
figure out what are the right

00:11:19.830 --> 00:11:21.490
things for us to do.

00:11:21.490 --> 00:11:22.300
And we used to have
this motive,

00:11:22.300 --> 00:11:24.050
like, act like an owner.

00:11:24.050 --> 00:11:27.110
So that really indirectly
helped me.

00:11:27.110 --> 00:11:29.520
Because I had no one to
go to for direction.

00:11:29.520 --> 00:11:30.690
I had to figure it out.

00:11:30.690 --> 00:11:33.230
And so it was very much a
sink or swim situation.

00:11:33.230 --> 00:11:37.190
And so I do think that that
is like a really valuable

00:11:37.190 --> 00:11:40.080
experience, where you need to
figure out yourself what are

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:42.980
the important things
to get done.

00:11:42.980 --> 00:11:45.710
MEGAN SMITH: One of the things
that I did, in thinking a

00:11:45.710 --> 00:11:48.110
little bit, we have an
extraordinary number of very

00:11:48.110 --> 00:11:50.860
talented women throughout
Google and also in

00:11:50.860 --> 00:11:51.670
leadership at Google.

00:11:51.670 --> 00:11:55.110
We're really lucky that our
company values diversity and

00:11:55.110 --> 00:11:55.770
talent inclusion.

00:11:55.770 --> 00:11:56.880
And so we see that--

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:00.420
on this particular panel, I
asked these guys because

00:12:00.420 --> 00:12:02.420
they're engineering and
product leaders.

00:12:02.420 --> 00:12:05.180
And they've built amazing
products that are--

00:12:05.180 --> 00:12:06.470
in the beginning, it was
millions of people.

00:12:06.470 --> 00:12:08.900
Now, really, all of you have
built things that are

00:12:08.900 --> 00:12:10.930
affecting billions of people.

00:12:10.930 --> 00:12:16.580
And so, maybe to sort of stay
with tech into innovation.

00:12:16.580 --> 00:12:17.930
How do you lead teams?

00:12:17.930 --> 00:12:19.780
How do you come up
with early ideas?

00:12:19.780 --> 00:12:21.235
How do you listen for ideas?

00:12:21.235 --> 00:12:25.390
Can you talk a little bit about
experiences being on

00:12:25.390 --> 00:12:28.540
this crazy rocketship and trying
to start new things and

00:12:28.540 --> 00:12:30.385
then turn them into what
they have become?

00:12:34.500 --> 00:12:37.820
ANGELA LAI: So things change in
the technical world very,

00:12:37.820 --> 00:12:38.570
very quickly.

00:12:38.570 --> 00:12:40.650
And there is our job,
and we deal with it.

00:12:40.650 --> 00:12:41.740
And the way that--

00:12:41.740 --> 00:12:44.630
speaking of engineering-- the
way that we do engineering

00:12:44.630 --> 00:12:46.630
some 10 years ago is very
different than the

00:12:46.630 --> 00:12:48.040
way that it is today.

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:52.490
And I will continue to vouch for
the really important part

00:12:52.490 --> 00:12:55.430
of the group culture that
we continue to learn.

00:12:55.430 --> 00:12:56.860
And we're not afraid
to change.

00:12:56.860 --> 00:12:58.970
And that's part of
the culture.

00:12:58.970 --> 00:13:01.950
And you need to continue
to spread that.

00:13:01.950 --> 00:13:05.830
And every time this spirit of
pushing yourself beyond the

00:13:05.830 --> 00:13:06.930
comfort zone--

00:13:06.930 --> 00:13:08.240
what more can we do?

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:12.560
And look outside of our boundary
boxes, and figure out

00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:15.260
can we try it and find
a way to try it?

00:13:15.260 --> 00:13:19.520
And I think try not to say no,
and really trying to continue

00:13:19.520 --> 00:13:21.990
to just sort of encourage
ourselves and continue to

00:13:21.990 --> 00:13:26.220
encourage a team to think about
ways of looking at our

00:13:26.220 --> 00:13:27.380
jobs differently.

00:13:27.380 --> 00:13:30.150
And some of my colleagues would
say every year they

00:13:30.150 --> 00:13:33.410
figure out how to blow up their
job and try it again.

00:13:33.410 --> 00:13:37.040
I mean, really get out off the
mode of what you're doing day

00:13:37.040 --> 00:13:40.360
to day, what seems to be
important to you today, and

00:13:40.360 --> 00:13:42.820
try to get a new perspective.

00:13:42.820 --> 00:13:45.830
And I think that constantly
putting ourselves in a new

00:13:45.830 --> 00:13:49.530
zone or thinking that well, if I
weren't me, if I were Susan,

00:13:49.530 --> 00:13:50.370
how would I do this?

00:13:50.370 --> 00:13:53.380
If I were somebody else outside
of Google, how would

00:13:53.380 --> 00:13:55.370
we look at this product?

00:13:55.370 --> 00:13:57.270
And I think, trying to get a
different perspective all the

00:13:57.270 --> 00:14:00.555
time is important.

00:14:00.555 --> 00:14:01.926
MEGAN SMITH: Any others?

00:14:01.926 --> 00:14:03.720
Talk about innovation, maybe.

00:14:03.720 --> 00:14:05.200
One of the things that
was interesting me

00:14:05.200 --> 00:14:07.060
was watching Susan.

00:14:07.060 --> 00:14:09.410
You were on maternity leave
and we bought DoubleClick.

00:14:09.410 --> 00:14:11.120
And we're just kind of wandering
around trying to

00:14:11.120 --> 00:14:12.320
figure out what to do.

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:14.410
Susan was a big part of deciding
to do that, but then

00:14:14.410 --> 00:14:16.160
she was gone when we were
doing integration.

00:14:16.160 --> 00:14:17.030
We need Susan.

00:14:17.030 --> 00:14:19.780
SUSAN WOJCICKI: It's because the
review took so long I was

00:14:19.780 --> 00:14:22.284
able to have a baby
in between.

00:14:22.284 --> 00:14:23.248
MEGAN SMITH: That's true.

00:14:23.248 --> 00:14:25.660
It was amazing.

00:14:25.660 --> 00:14:27.380
Just how do you--

00:14:27.380 --> 00:14:30.630
all a sudden, thousands of
people join the company.

00:14:30.630 --> 00:14:31.200
Would do you do?

00:14:31.200 --> 00:14:32.030
How do you lead?

00:14:32.030 --> 00:14:36.040
How do you help people put
something like that together?

00:14:36.040 --> 00:14:38.250
SUSAN WOJCICKI: Yeah, I think
that the trick on innovation

00:14:38.250 --> 00:14:41.420
and on managing teams and
figuring out the right sorts

00:14:41.420 --> 00:14:43.690
of things to do is, first of
all, to figure out where

00:14:43.690 --> 00:14:45.340
you're going--

00:14:45.340 --> 00:14:48.430
and being able to say
this is the vision.

00:14:48.430 --> 00:14:51.750
This is where we know we want
to be in two years or like

00:14:51.750 --> 00:14:55.250
next year-- and then
working backwards.

00:14:55.250 --> 00:14:59.570
And so if you have a vision,
everybody can rally around.

00:14:59.570 --> 00:15:01.150
Everyone can start to
understand what's

00:15:01.150 --> 00:15:01.910
important about it.

00:15:01.910 --> 00:15:05.230
They can be motivated by it.

00:15:05.230 --> 00:15:07.140
And then you can start figuring
out what are the

00:15:07.140 --> 00:15:08.910
things that we need to
do to get there.

00:15:08.910 --> 00:15:10.980
And so that I think is always
like the number

00:15:10.980 --> 00:15:12.790
one thing to do.

00:15:12.790 --> 00:15:14.690
And then I think the second
thing is just putting the

00:15:14.690 --> 00:15:20.030
right people in place
and questioning.

00:15:20.030 --> 00:15:23.060
There's always like
a challenge of--

00:15:23.060 --> 00:15:27.640
teams think they can only do
this much, but then if you

00:15:27.640 --> 00:15:32.070
inspire them or challenge them
or they have to, they somehow

00:15:32.070 --> 00:15:34.210
manage to go a little
bit further or do it

00:15:34.210 --> 00:15:35.240
a little bit better.

00:15:35.240 --> 00:15:38.990
And there's always a challenge
of how do you get people to

00:15:38.990 --> 00:15:39.910
really want to do that.

00:15:39.910 --> 00:15:42.060
And I think a big part is
believing in that mission,

00:15:42.060 --> 00:15:44.980
being excited, being compelled,
believing that it's

00:15:44.980 --> 00:15:47.375
what they want to do.

00:15:47.375 --> 00:15:51.330
GAYATRI RAJAN: And I think
another important side, even

00:15:51.330 --> 00:15:55.910
as you get people rallied around
the objective and have

00:15:55.910 --> 00:16:00.010
them think about new ideas to
excel, you have to be pretty

00:16:00.010 --> 00:16:03.900
strict and very disciplined
about making sure that the

00:16:03.900 --> 00:16:07.940
ideas that aren't helping that
vision, that they don't take

00:16:07.940 --> 00:16:11.920
up air time and they don't
distract from the mission.

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:15.390
So that can often be the
harder part of the job,

00:16:15.390 --> 00:16:18.690
because it's so much nicer
getting people forward.

00:16:18.690 --> 00:16:22.530
It's harder sometimes
restraining.

00:16:22.530 --> 00:16:23.770
But it has to be done.

00:16:23.770 --> 00:16:25.090
So it's a balance.

00:16:25.090 --> 00:16:28.120
But as Susan said, if you have
the right vision and if you

00:16:28.120 --> 00:16:32.640
communicated it, people will
come up with the ideas.

00:16:32.640 --> 00:16:36.840
It's almost an easy job for a
leader to just harvest that.

00:16:36.840 --> 00:16:39.520
MEGAN SMITH: To crowd-source,
to harvest them.

00:16:39.520 --> 00:16:41.470
Yeah, Anna, go ahead.

00:16:41.470 --> 00:16:44.490
ANNA PATTERSON: I also try to
get people who actually really

00:16:44.490 --> 00:16:49.160
believe in the vision and who
have a lot of passion about

00:16:49.160 --> 00:16:50.090
contributing.

00:16:50.090 --> 00:16:53.290
And with every project, there's
the exciting bits and

00:16:53.290 --> 00:16:54.540
the boring this.

00:16:54.540 --> 00:16:58.140
And so I try to actually give
each person an exciting bit

00:16:58.140 --> 00:16:58.900
and a boring bit.

00:16:58.900 --> 00:17:01.456
So they actually get the
boring bit done.

00:17:01.456 --> 00:17:03.360
And they go on to the
exciting bit.

00:17:03.360 --> 00:17:05.359
And the great thing about that
is then you can give them

00:17:05.359 --> 00:17:09.119
another boring bit, right?

00:17:09.119 --> 00:17:09.640
MEGAN SMITH: Good system.

00:17:09.640 --> 00:17:11.750
We have a really great
OKR system--

00:17:11.750 --> 00:17:12.960
Objective and Key Results.

00:17:12.960 --> 00:17:14.609
And we really use
it with a lot of

00:17:14.609 --> 00:17:15.710
discipline within the company.

00:17:15.710 --> 00:17:17.700
I don't know if anyone wants to
say a sentence about sort

00:17:17.700 --> 00:17:21.380
of how we do that, what we
do with the process.

00:17:21.380 --> 00:17:23.109
It's a process we drive
ourselves crazy

00:17:23.109 --> 00:17:24.420
with it, but we do.

00:17:24.420 --> 00:17:25.960
ANGELA LAI: So those objectives
and results

00:17:25.960 --> 00:17:29.500
actually speaks to how we just
[INAUDIBLE] ourselves.

00:17:29.500 --> 00:17:31.470
One thing that is important,
like what Susan was saying,

00:17:31.470 --> 00:17:33.510
having a vision is knowing
what you're

00:17:33.510 --> 00:17:34.530
trying to drive to.

00:17:34.530 --> 00:17:37.250
So the objective list, what
you're actually trying to get

00:17:37.250 --> 00:17:42.080
to, not the task that you're
trying to do, not how you're

00:17:42.080 --> 00:17:43.130
going to get there--
is actually

00:17:43.130 --> 00:17:45.290
describe the actual objective.

00:17:45.290 --> 00:17:48.690
And the key results, as a
result-driven company, is to

00:17:48.690 --> 00:17:54.060
actually define what makes you
successful, what makes us

00:17:54.060 --> 00:17:56.240
happy about-- what we think
whether we have

00:17:56.240 --> 00:17:57.820
achieved the objective.

00:17:57.820 --> 00:18:01.760
And so it's not about creating
a task list, even thought we

00:18:01.760 --> 00:18:03.463
have to figure out which is
boring bits and which are the

00:18:03.463 --> 00:18:06.580
exciting bits that eventually
we work on, but as a way to

00:18:06.580 --> 00:18:09.540
get everybody to be empowered
to understand the goal and

00:18:09.540 --> 00:18:11.920
objectives of what
every team, every

00:18:11.920 --> 00:18:14.910
individual, the overall company--

00:18:14.910 --> 00:18:17.230
at the different levels, we
define these objectives and

00:18:17.230 --> 00:18:17.850
key results.

00:18:17.850 --> 00:18:20.030
So people believe in what
they're doing, understand

00:18:20.030 --> 00:18:22.880
where we're trying to drive to,
and then it really has the

00:18:22.880 --> 00:18:25.870
part of responsibility and drive
towards the same place.

00:18:25.870 --> 00:18:28.526
So it's a very empowering way
for the team to figure out how

00:18:28.526 --> 00:18:31.810
to get in sync, and how to
prioritize [INAUDIBLE] what's

00:18:31.810 --> 00:18:33.770
important and what we're
trying to get to.

00:18:33.770 --> 00:18:37.320
And we can also look back at it,
and say well, we planned

00:18:37.320 --> 00:18:41.610
that and sort of do a
retrospective on was that a

00:18:41.610 --> 00:18:43.500
good set of things to measure
to start with.

00:18:43.500 --> 00:18:45.930
And if we were measure our own
success by that, what do we

00:18:45.930 --> 00:18:46.700
learn from it?

00:18:46.700 --> 00:18:49.500
And that's how we continue to
innovate by reflecting upon

00:18:49.500 --> 00:18:53.596
ourselves what we've actually
done periodically.

00:18:53.596 --> 00:18:55.480
SUSAN WOJCICKI: I was just going
to say I think that the

00:18:55.480 --> 00:18:59.210
OKRs are sometimes like a really
