products we build, they're

00:22:34.010 --> 00:22:35.510
intended for men and women.

00:22:35.510 --> 00:22:37.860
And the product that I'm
on, Google Offers--

00:22:37.860 --> 00:22:40.020
I mean, women like shopping.

00:22:40.020 --> 00:22:42.200
This is something that's--

00:22:42.200 --> 00:22:43.670
MEGAN SMITH: And are responsible
for a lot of

00:22:43.670 --> 00:22:45.180
shopping across the family.

00:22:45.180 --> 00:22:46.430
GAYATRI RAJAN: A very
loyal bias.

00:22:50.740 --> 00:22:52.720
It's clear that everything
we do, we're

00:22:52.720 --> 00:22:55.780
doing for men and women.

00:22:55.780 --> 00:22:59.520
Somewhere in the pipeline,
there's a perception that

00:22:59.520 --> 00:23:02.050
technology is very male.

00:23:02.050 --> 00:23:03.560
And I think what
we have to do--

00:23:03.560 --> 00:23:07.380
and this is the responsibility
of everyone in the room who is

00:23:07.380 --> 00:23:08.630
in technology--

00:23:10.450 --> 00:23:13.140
is to tell the story of
what we do, in a way

00:23:13.140 --> 00:23:15.700
that appeals to girls.

00:23:15.700 --> 00:23:17.720
And I say girls, not women,
because by the time they're

00:23:17.720 --> 00:23:19.440
women, it's too late.

00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:23.090
So we have to find a
way to translate--

00:23:23.090 --> 00:23:25.460
if they're not interested in
video games, find a way--

00:23:25.460 --> 00:23:31.130
maybe it's a social game or a
game around philanthropy or

00:23:31.130 --> 00:23:34.300
giving that appeals to them and
really find a way to tell

00:23:34.300 --> 00:23:37.730
the story of technology in a way
that resonates with women.

00:23:37.730 --> 00:23:39.400
I don't think we do that now.

00:23:42.760 --> 00:23:45.150
ANNA PATTERSON: I think as a
career, it's very social.

00:23:45.150 --> 00:23:49.590
And I think media
portrays it--

00:23:49.590 --> 00:23:52.540
and a lot of people, their
stereotypes in other

00:23:52.540 --> 00:23:55.110
industries think it's
a very loner thing.

00:23:55.110 --> 00:23:59.470
And actually working in an
engineering team is a

00:23:59.470 --> 00:24:03.060
remarkably together thing, like
rowing crew together.

00:24:03.060 --> 00:24:08.100
I mean, it's really intense
social interactions and a lot

00:24:08.100 --> 00:24:09.230
of teamwork.

00:24:09.230 --> 00:24:13.090
And so I think women could
bring a lot to it.

00:24:13.090 --> 00:24:16.120
And they bring a lot
to their teams.

00:24:16.120 --> 00:24:17.180
SUSAN WOJCICKI: But I'm
always surprised

00:24:17.180 --> 00:24:18.460
there aren't more women.

00:24:18.460 --> 00:24:21.840
Because I think if you look at
technologies afield, it's such

00:24:21.840 --> 00:24:23.740
a new field.

00:24:23.740 --> 00:24:25.670
And there's so much
opportunity.

00:24:25.670 --> 00:24:27.930
And to me, that means
that there isn't

00:24:27.930 --> 00:24:32.100
really time to be biased.

00:24:32.100 --> 00:24:35.340
If you have a great product, it
doesn't really matter who's

00:24:35.340 --> 00:24:37.430
the person who's running
that product.

00:24:37.430 --> 00:24:41.200
If you have a great company,
if you have a great idea,

00:24:41.200 --> 00:24:42.060
there's lots of opportunity.

00:24:42.060 --> 00:24:46.460
There's so much opportunity here
that women have that, I

00:24:46.460 --> 00:24:49.490
think once they're in the
system, they're able to

00:24:49.490 --> 00:24:50.330
achieve a lot.

00:24:50.330 --> 00:24:53.400
But what the challenge is, and
actually you once told me this

00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:55.770
great quote, like, there are
lots of-- what did you say?

00:24:55.770 --> 00:24:56.960
Megan told me.

00:24:56.960 --> 00:25:00.170
Basically you have to know that
opportunity is there.

00:25:00.170 --> 00:25:03.230
If you get here and you get in
technology, then you have

00:25:03.230 --> 00:25:04.410
those opportunities.

00:25:04.410 --> 00:25:06.630
But if you don't even know those
opportunities are there,

00:25:06.630 --> 00:25:09.910
you'll never actually
get there

00:25:09.910 --> 00:25:11.510
MEGAN SMITH: We're all in a
group called Women at Goog--

