in fact, there's 19 employee
resource groups at Google that

00:25:14.300 --> 00:25:17.885
were created by the various
teams to interconnect us.

00:25:17.885 --> 00:25:19.650
And actually, turns out there's
30,000 Googlers.

00:25:19.650 --> 00:25:23.110
And I think there's 12,000 or
15,000 people on these lists.

00:25:23.110 --> 00:25:25.370
So Women At is one that
we participate in.

00:25:25.370 --> 00:25:28.180
And some of you guys are in the
Google Women Engineering.

00:25:28.180 --> 00:25:32.440
Gayglers, VetNet, Black Googlers
Network, Hispanic

00:25:32.440 --> 00:25:35.400
Googlers Network, Filipino
Googlers, Googler American

00:25:35.400 --> 00:25:38.530
Indian Network-- just amazing
groups of people.

00:25:38.530 --> 00:25:46.600
And so we were talking all about
this and how a lot of

00:25:46.600 --> 00:25:49.720
people out of the world don't
know about the world we live

00:25:49.720 --> 00:25:51.870
in and how exciting they are.

00:25:51.870 --> 00:25:55.260
And so how do you tell people
especially, when we're often

00:25:55.260 --> 00:25:57.870
in countries that are so highly
racially divided or

00:25:57.870 --> 00:26:01.460
countries that are gender
divided, or--

00:26:01.460 --> 00:26:04.280
sometimes, often for our
companies, we're hiring so

00:26:04.280 --> 00:26:06.090
fast, we're like who knows
someone from this?

00:26:06.090 --> 00:26:07.360
And so we just keep

00:26:07.360 --> 00:26:08.780
perpetrating the talent circles.

00:26:08.780 --> 00:26:10.570
And instead like, who
knows a woman?

00:26:10.570 --> 00:26:12.860
Who knows someone from an
underrepresented group, in

00:26:12.860 --> 00:26:14.580
addition to just asking
the question in

00:26:14.580 --> 00:26:15.820
general, to get them in.

00:26:15.820 --> 00:26:19.810
Because there's a wonderful
actual interview with three

00:26:19.810 --> 00:26:21.890
African American CEOs here in
Silicon Valley, and they're

00:26:21.890 --> 00:26:24.740
saying exactly this, which is,
if you can get here, it's a

00:26:24.740 --> 00:26:27.490
meritocracy in many ways.

00:26:27.490 --> 00:26:31.740
But finding out we're here, the
tech industry is here, is

00:26:31.740 --> 00:26:34.990
an important thing
to make happen.

00:26:34.990 --> 00:26:38.950
So one of the things that--
you mentioned media.

00:26:38.950 --> 00:26:41.950
Gayatri organized a great event
last year, which was a

00:26:41.950 --> 00:26:44.420
conference of the various
women leaders and folks

00:26:44.420 --> 00:26:45.070
getting together.

00:26:45.070 --> 00:26:46.860
And we were lucky to
have Geena Davis.

00:26:46.860 --> 00:26:49.320
And I don't know if anyone wants
to mention some of her

00:26:49.320 --> 00:26:52.210
findings, but she did an
extraordinary study of the

00:26:52.210 --> 00:26:56.220
media that we all watch for
six-year-olds and under.

00:26:56.220 --> 00:26:58.690
And so you were talking about
sort of what you see, like

00:26:58.690 --> 00:27:00.590
this loner engineer
or the loner.

00:27:00.590 --> 00:27:03.590
But actually the portrayal
of women is

00:27:03.590 --> 00:27:05.090
the interesting there.

00:27:05.090 --> 00:27:09.000
I think she told us that it's
two to three men or boys

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.830
on-screen to one girl
or women in

00:27:11.830 --> 00:27:13.650
cartoons and various things.

00:27:13.650 --> 00:27:16.210
She has a funny joke about
the film Nemo--

00:27:16.210 --> 00:27:18.410
wonderful, one of my favorite
Pixar films.

00:27:18.410 --> 00:27:22.610
But how many women or
girls in the ocean?

00:27:22.610 --> 00:27:24.060
Yeah, there's one.

00:27:24.060 --> 00:27:25.300
So, it's Dory.

00:27:25.300 --> 00:27:27.780
I think there might be some
little girls on the swimming

00:27:27.780 --> 00:27:28.520
fish school.

00:27:28.520 --> 00:27:32.470
And mom gets killed of course.

00:27:32.470 --> 00:27:33.660
But there's one.

00:27:33.660 --> 00:27:35.370
So that's like really
happening in

00:27:35.370 --> 00:27:38.970
the ocean, I guess.

00:27:38.970 --> 00:27:43.060
So just that we grow up with
this image that Smurfette,

00:27:43.060 --> 00:27:45.880
that the world is made of lots
of boys with one girl.

00:27:45.880 --> 00:27:47.400
And so we imagine this.

00:27:47.400 --> 00:27:50.300
And the one that was most
telling, Anna, to your point

00:27:50.300 --> 00:27:52.500
is about jobs.

00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:53.780
Its that 80%--

00:27:53.780 --> 00:27:54.790
yeah, 80%--

00:27:54.790 --> 00:27:56.610
what was the stat?--
are held--

00:27:56.610 --> 00:28:00.140
ANNA PATTERSON: 80% of the jobs
in these cartoons were

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:01.155
held by men.

00:28:01.155 --> 00:28:01.530
MEGAN SMITH: Right.

00:28:01.530 --> 00:28:04.880
ANNA PATTERSON: Or 80% of the
jobs in shows targeted for the

00:28:04.880 --> 00:28:07.410
under six-year-olds
were held by men.

00:28:07.410 --> 00:28:08.590
MEGAN SMITH: So the boys
are learning that

00:28:08.590 --> 00:28:09.410
men hold the jobs.

00:28:09.410 --> 00:28:11.700
And these jobs, the girls are
learning that-- in fact, Geena

00:28:11.700 --> 00:28:13.540
says boys will be boys and
girls will be boys.

00:28:13.540 --> 00:28:17.220
You have To translate to be a
boy, to think about being a

00:28:17.220 --> 00:28:21.300
scientist or an engineer or a
businessperson or a lawyer--

00:28:21.300 --> 00:28:22.740
examples of people
who are not even

00:28:22.740 --> 00:28:25.800
depicted in the 20% women.

