We work really closely
with them.

00:35:07.480 --> 00:35:11.860
And we also try do a lot of
scholarship work with all

00:35:11.860 --> 00:35:14.800
different underrepresented
people, with women, a lot of

00:35:14.800 --> 00:35:16.870
recruiting, a lot of
those pieces--

00:35:16.870 --> 00:35:18.790
Susan, you had a couple.

00:35:18.790 --> 00:35:19.990
Were you going to
say something?

00:35:19.990 --> 00:35:22.340
There's just a range of programs
that we're doing.

00:35:22.340 --> 00:35:24.230
And also like this,
like showing up.

00:35:24.230 --> 00:35:28.030
There's actually a question in
here about one of the internal

00:35:28.030 --> 00:35:31.870
meetings we posted that's
about one of the Dory

00:35:31.870 --> 00:35:35.850
questions or moderator asking
why the internal meeting only

00:35:35.850 --> 00:35:36.670
had men talking.

00:35:36.670 --> 00:35:37.640
It was a search quality
meeting.

00:35:37.640 --> 00:35:39.550
I think they were talking
about spell check.

00:35:39.550 --> 00:35:42.780
And actually typically, our
teams are more balanced.

00:35:42.780 --> 00:35:44.640
And so I don't know why that
particular meeting--

00:35:44.640 --> 00:35:46.820
and it actually is a good
example where someone's

00:35:46.820 --> 00:35:49.630
checking us and saying hey,
you're putting a Google image

00:35:49.630 --> 00:35:51.360
of an engineering meeting
out there.

00:35:51.360 --> 00:35:53.800
Make sure that the women in the
team-- or choose a meeting

00:35:53.800 --> 00:35:55.380
where there are women or
underrepresented women--

00:35:55.380 --> 00:35:58.286
everybody's in the team in
the way we normally work.

00:35:58.286 --> 00:36:00.360
So it's really important--

00:36:00.360 --> 00:36:02.630
back to the media point--
what you project and

00:36:02.630 --> 00:36:03.575
who you try to help.

00:36:03.575 --> 00:36:04.000
Yeah.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:04.985
SUSAN WOJCICKI: I mean, I think,
the other thing I would

00:36:04.985 --> 00:36:08.020
add is that I think it's not
just there's like one iconic

00:36:08.020 --> 00:36:11.180
women, but that actually within
the organization,

00:36:11.180 --> 00:36:14.590
everybody feels like there are
people in my group that are

00:36:14.590 --> 00:36:17.880
like me, whatever
that group is.

00:36:17.880 --> 00:36:20.990
And I think if you look across
our organization, we have--

00:36:20.990 --> 00:36:23.010
because we've worked really hard
at it-- we have a good

00:36:23.010 --> 00:36:25.950
women representation across
different groups, across

00:36:25.950 --> 00:36:28.600
sales, across engineering,
across all areas.

00:36:28.600 --> 00:36:30.920
But from a technical standpoint,
it definitely--

00:36:30.920 --> 00:36:35.280
I mean, we have to work really
hard to get women computer

00:36:35.280 --> 00:36:38.030
scientists and software
engineers into the program.

00:36:38.030 --> 00:36:42.550
So we do have special recruiting
to try to increase

00:36:42.550 --> 00:36:43.800
that group.

00:36:51.159 --> 00:36:51.640
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:36:51.640 --> 00:36:55.590
So my question would be do you
think it's worth hiring women

00:36:55.590 --> 00:36:58.610
that are just interested
about technology and

00:36:58.610 --> 00:37:00.230
then training them?

00:37:00.230 --> 00:37:01.480
Do you have some program
like that?

00:37:04.860 --> 00:37:05.960
MEGAN SMITH: We do some
programs like that.

00:37:05.960 --> 00:37:11.320
I actually heard a really
interesting one by-- oh my

00:37:11.320 --> 00:37:12.940
god, what's the name
of the company?

00:37:12.940 --> 00:37:14.730
Social--

00:37:14.730 --> 00:37:16.270
huge company.

00:37:16.270 --> 00:37:17.880
There's a group in DC.

00:37:17.880 --> 00:37:19.260
They're called-- it's
like Groupon.

00:37:19.260 --> 00:37:19.540
Social?

00:37:19.540 --> 00:37:20.370
AUDIENCE: Living Social.

00:37:20.370 --> 00:37:20.890
MEGAN SMITH: Living
Social, thank you!

00:37:20.890 --> 00:37:23.340
I don't know why I-- sorry,
Living Social!

00:37:23.340 --> 00:37:25.860
Anyway, I met this amazing guy
from Living Social, and he's

00:37:25.860 --> 00:37:29.590
been training people in DC in
general on computer science,

00:37:29.590 --> 00:37:31.980
and has been making sure the
classes are actually

00:37:31.980 --> 00:37:34.010
half-balanced, men and women,
just thinking of

00:37:34.010 --> 00:37:35.040
very talented people.

00:37:35.040 --> 00:37:38.965
And I think he's doing almost
like a three-month onboarding

00:37:38.965 --> 00:37:41.170
and then pulling people in,
because they just need more

00:37:41.170 --> 00:37:43.175
tech folks where they are.

00:37:43.175 --> 00:37:47.020
I also heard an amazing thing
that Code Academy is 40%

00:37:47.020 --> 00:37:49.100
women, which is great.

00:37:49.100 --> 00:37:50.550
So definitely.

00:37:50.550 --> 00:37:53.240
We also have a wonderful program
called BODL practicum,

00:37:53.240 --> 00:37:56.140
which is taking underrepresented
minority top

00:37:56.140 --> 00:37:57.680
talent, focusing-- getting--
pulling them

00:37:57.680 --> 00:38:00.020
into computer science.

00:38:00.020 --> 00:38:01.505
Because we need more people
from those backgrounds

00:38:01.505 --> 00:38:02.620
in our field too.

00:38:02.620 --> 00:38:05.350
So, definitely, we are part of
that, and we're also funding

00:38:05.350 --> 00:38:06.490
some of the programs
like that.

00:38:06.490 --> 00:38:09.360
And if people have ideas like
that, we want to hear more.

00:38:09.360 --> 00:38:11.890
SUSAN WOJCICKI: I mean,
I would also say--

00:38:11.890 --> 00:38:14.250
Google as a representative tech
company-- we have many

00:38:14.250 --> 00:38:16.595
jobs that are for people
who are not technical.

00:38:16.595 --> 00:38:17.460
We have sales.

00:38:17.460 --> 00:38:18.500
We have marketing.

00:38:18.500 --> 00:38:19.650
We have operations.

00:38:19.650 --> 00:38:21.360
We have lots and lots
of different areas.

00:38:21.360 --> 00:38:24.000
And so anyone who has an
interest can enter through

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:26.060
multiple doors.

00:38:26.060 --> 00:38:29.510
And if they choose, they
can go back and get

00:38:29.510 --> 00:38:30.870
more technical skills.

00:38:30.870 --> 00:38:32.320
But to be an engineer,
you need to have

00:38:32.320 --> 00:38:33.680
the technical degree.

00:38:36.750 --> 00:38:37.924
MEGAN SMITH: The
question here.

00:38:37.924 --> 00:38:39.160
Grab your mic.

00:38:39.160 --> 00:38:40.330
Go grab your mic.

00:38:40.330 --> 00:38:42.287
SUSAN WOJCICKI: --or technical
experience.

00:38:42.287 --> 00:38:44.020
MEGAN SMITH: Over here.

00:38:44.020 --> 00:38:47.060
AUDIENCE: My question is in
regards to the statement that

00:38:47.060 --> 00:38:50.210
was made a few moments ago
about it being a very

00:38:50.210 --> 00:38:53.140
supportive culture at Google
and how great it is to have

00:38:53.140 --> 00:38:54.810
someone in the room
who's like you.

00:38:54.810 --> 00:38:58.330
So what about those of us who
are not fortunate enough to be

00:38:58.330 --> 00:39:00.710
in that type of environment,
where there is not someone in

00:39:00.710 --> 00:39:03.720
the room like us, what
recommendations or suggestions

00:39:03.720 --> 00:39:05.525
do you have for women
in those situations?

00:39:10.640 --> 00:39:12.740
MEGAN SMITH: Probably everybody
has been in that

00:39:12.740 --> 00:39:15.040
position, where you're sort
of the only person--

00:39:15.040 --> 00:39:15.920
you're the only woman.

00:39:15.920 --> 00:39:19.260
Or you're the only person
from wherever.

00:39:19.260 --> 00:39:22.580
Maybe talk a little bit about
strategies in that situation.

00:39:22.580 --> 00:39:23.850
SUSAN WOJCICKI: I mean,
I think it's a hard

00:39:23.850 --> 00:39:25.200
situation to be in.

00:39:25.200 --> 00:39:29.500
And I'll just say like two
things that come to mind.

00:39:29.500 --> 00:39:32.310
I think first of all, I worked
at one organization before

00:39:32.310 --> 00:39:40.030
Google where that maybe I felt
a little more isolated in.

00:39:40.030 --> 00:39:43.900
But what I found is there were a
couple other women that were

00:39:43.900 --> 00:39:45.100
there in that organization.

00:39:45.100 --> 00:39:48.880
And we started to get together
on a regular basis.

00:39:48.880 --> 00:39:51.740
We wound up having lunch
once a week or

00:39:51.740 --> 00:39:52.500
once every two weeks.

00:39:52.500 --> 00:39:55.110
And I found that actually even
though it was a small group,

00:39:55.110 --> 00:39:57.870
by actually connecting, we were
able to form a pretty

00:39:57.870 --> 00:39:59.400
strong bond.

00:39:59.400 --> 00:40:03.340
And having some set of people
that I could connect to made a

00:40:03.340 --> 00:40:05.400
really big difference in like
that they had shared

00:40:05.400 --> 00:40:08.420
experiences about that
organization as well.

00:40:08.420 --> 00:40:11.160
And then I say the second thing
too is that ultimately,

00:40:11.160 --> 00:40:17.560
it's believing in what you're
doing and trying to get what

00:40:17.560 --> 00:40:19.420
you think is the most important
thing to be done as

00:40:19.420 --> 00:40:23.720
efficiently as possible and to
make sure that your work is

00:40:23.720 --> 00:40:25.040
able to shine through.

00:40:25.040 --> 00:40:27.120
And then if ultimately you feel
like you can't, for one

00:40:27.120 --> 00:40:29.960
reason or another, to find
a place where you can be

00:40:29.960 --> 00:40:32.260
recognized for the work
you're doing.

00:40:32.260 --> 00:40:34.360
ANGELA LAI: It is definitely a
difficult to be the only one--

00:40:34.360 --> 00:40:39.060
I'm the only woman in my
graduating class for many

00:40:39.060 --> 00:40:40.760
years ago now.

00:40:40.760 --> 00:40:41.460
And it was a small class.

00:40:41.460 --> 00:40:46.040
It was about, I think, it was
only 50 or 60 engineers.

00:40:46.040 --> 00:40:48.900
And I find myself in a lot of
design reviews and engineering

00:40:48.900 --> 00:40:51.740
meetings, where I'm the only
woman in the room.

00:40:51.740 --> 00:40:54.000
What I've found at Google, and
hopefully you can find this in

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:56.600
other parts of the culture,
a lot of men are also very

00:40:56.600 --> 00:40:57.720
supportive.

00:40:57.720 --> 00:41:01.530
Our last VP, Alan Eustace, is
a very great champion for

00:41:01.530 --> 00:41:05.890
women in technology, as well
as my manager, Jeff Huber.

00:41:05.890 --> 00:41:07.290
These are the senior
vice presidents

00:41:07.290 --> 00:41:08.230
that will speak out.

00:41:08.230 --> 00:41:12.380
And they will find a connection
by proxy in women

00:41:12.380 --> 00:41:13.480
they support.

00:41:13.480 --> 00:41:17.190
And I have found actually in
technology, the culture of

00:41:17.190 --> 00:41:20.940
technology is very rationally
objective.

00:41:20.940 --> 00:41:25.100
And I find a lot of men to be
actually great support for

00:41:25.100 --> 00:41:26.320
things that we need to do it.

00:41:26.320 --> 00:41:28.550
And by proxy of them thinking
about how they support their

00:41:28.550 --> 00:41:33.330
family, how they support their
daughters, and the experience

00:41:33.330 --> 00:41:38.210
in these proxy situations, it's
good conversations to try

00:41:38.210 --> 00:41:41.130
to create the bond.

00:41:41.130 --> 00:41:45.810
And also feeling confident to
not feel isolated is important

00:41:45.810 --> 00:41:47.870
in finding other allies
that can help.

00:41:47.870 --> 00:41:51.240
I think it is important.

00:41:51.240 --> 00:41:53.470
MEGAN SMITH: You guys mentioned
Alan Eustace, he ran

00:41:53.470 --> 00:41:55.710
engineering, much of
engineering, for many years

00:41:55.710 --> 00:41:58.010
and leads a lot of search now.

00:41:58.010 --> 00:41:59.700
He shared an office
with Anita Borg.

00:41:59.700 --> 00:42:02.190
So he has high consciousness
about women's issues.

00:42:02.190 --> 00:42:05.050
But he runs studies a lot--

00:42:05.050 --> 00:42:10.130
I remember he did a study where
he was wondering whether

00:42:10.130 --> 00:42:12.170
women were not--

00:42:12.170 --> 00:42:16.350
in Google, you can nominate
yourself for promotion.

00:42:16.350 --> 00:42:18.550
Or your manager might nominate
you for promotion.

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:19.520
And then you go through
a process of

00:42:19.520 --> 00:42:21.830
very transparent culture.

00:42:21.830 --> 00:42:24.380
And they were noticing that
women were not nominating

00:42:24.380 --> 00:42:26.650
themselves as much as men.

00:42:26.650 --> 00:42:30.100
So they ran a study to see are
women being promoted as much.

00:42:30.100 --> 00:42:31.510
And it turned out that the
women that were being

00:42:31.510 --> 00:42:36.100
promoted, the managers were then
taking care of nominating

00:42:36.100 --> 00:42:37.930
women and making sure
that was happening.

00:42:37.930 --> 00:42:42.080
But something where he wrote an
active email to the company

00:42:42.080 --> 00:42:46.400
asking that women nominate
yourself and really

00:42:46.400 --> 00:42:47.270
encouraging people.

00:42:47.270 --> 00:42:50.520
And I think there is some
amount of maybe--

00:42:50.520 --> 00:42:53.730
a friend of mine who won the
Anita Borg award, Mary Lou

00:42:53.730 --> 00:42:58.430
Jepson, has synthetic hormones
from a pituitary tumor, and

00:42:58.430 --> 00:43:00.630
she ended up taking testosterone
and found that

00:43:00.630 --> 00:43:01.800
her confidence levels went up.

00:43:01.800 --> 00:43:04.131
So I don't know, somebody
should study this.

00:43:04.131 --> 00:43:05.725
She found other things too.

00:43:05.725 --> 00:43:07.720
But watch the video
of her speech.

00:43:07.720 --> 00:43:08.490
It's great.

00:43:08.490 --> 00:43:11.530
But confidence-- and so she said
she really had a lot more

00:43:11.530 --> 00:43:14.440
understanding of the men she was
managing and working with

00:43:14.440 --> 00:43:16.190
from that experience, which
I thought was really an

00:43:16.190 --> 00:43:19.160
extraordinary thing for
her and to hear that.

00:43:19.160 --> 00:43:21.950
And so think a little bit about
confidence and maybe

00:43:21.950 --> 00:43:24.750
there are gender differences
and maybe confidence or

00:43:24.750 --> 00:43:27.030
feeling like the impostor
syndrome-- like if they only

00:43:27.030 --> 00:43:28.650
find me out.

00:43:28.650 --> 00:43:29.510
I don't know what I'm doing.

00:43:29.510 --> 00:43:30.720
But you really do.

00:43:30.720 --> 00:43:32.900
And having the confidence to put
yourself up for promotion,

00:43:32.900 --> 00:43:33.760
in this case.

00:43:33.760 --> 00:43:36.190
But also I think the more
important thing there--

00:43:36.190 --> 00:43:39.220
and your point of connecting
to people-- was Alan also

00:43:39.220 --> 00:43:43.870
stepping up to make sure there
was space for people in the

00:43:43.870 --> 00:43:46.060
community and that they
were going to become

00:43:46.060 --> 00:43:47.220
leaders in the same way.

00:43:47.220 --> 00:43:48.630
It was really important.

00:43:51.920 --> 00:43:53.880
So let's see.

00:43:53.880 --> 00:43:55.060
We have a bunch of different
questions.

00:43:55.060 --> 00:43:58.410
One of them actually is
one that's sort of a

00:43:58.410 --> 00:43:59.690
controversy out there.

00:43:59.690 --> 00:44:02.350
If any of you have read the
Anne-Marie Slaughter recent

00:44:02.350 --> 00:44:04.600
article in The Atlantic entitled
"Why Women Still

00:44:04.600 --> 00:44:08.030
Can't Have It All," regarding
the unsolved problem facing

00:44:08.030 --> 00:44:10.260
highly successful women who
value time with their

00:44:10.260 --> 00:44:13.260
families, what is
your reaction?

00:44:13.260 --> 00:44:17.970
That'd be an interesting one to
talk about, because there

00:44:17.970 --> 00:44:21.680
are trade offs and challenges
with balancing work and family

00:44:21.680 --> 00:44:24.120
and relationships.

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:27.140
One extraordinary thing is that
both Anna and Susan have

00:44:27.140 --> 00:44:29.710
four children under 12
or 12 and under?

00:44:29.710 --> 00:44:31.000
Yeah?

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:34.420
So, just you guys are doing that
all the time at scale.

00:44:37.228 --> 00:44:39.380
So I don't know if either
of you or any of

00:44:39.380 --> 00:44:42.240
you guys have comments.

00:44:42.240 --> 00:44:44.730
We have two boys, and
you know it's--

00:44:44.730 --> 00:44:47.600
I think technology is a little
more forgiving than maybe

00:44:47.600 --> 00:44:51.660
perhaps, say, Anne-Marie, who
was in the State Department, I

00:44:51.660 --> 00:44:56.050
think, in a diplomatic role,
traveling quite frequently.

00:44:56.050 --> 00:44:58.430
I remember once talking to
Sergey and giving a tour.

00:44:58.430 --> 00:45:00.180
And he walked in and someone
said are people

00:45:00.180 --> 00:45:00.840
here all the time?

00:45:00.840 --> 00:45:01.640
And he's like oh yes.

00:45:01.640 --> 00:45:03.770
They're here from very early
in the morning till

00:45:03.770 --> 00:45:05.130
very late at night.

00:45:05.130 --> 00:45:08.610
Just not the same people.

00:45:08.610 --> 00:45:10.730
So we have this culture where
our founders from the

00:45:10.730 --> 00:45:14.520
beginning were very open
to meritocracy.

00:45:14.520 --> 00:45:15.380
Get the work done.

00:45:15.380 --> 00:45:16.550
We don't care when
you're here.

00:45:16.550 --> 00:45:19.980
And I don't know if you guys
have thoughts about that.

00:45:19.980 --> 00:45:22.005
SUSAN WOJCICKI: I mean, I
read the article too.

00:45:22.005 --> 00:45:24.580
I don't know how many
of you have read it.

00:45:24.580 --> 00:45:25.880
I mean, I think these
are very personal

00:45:25.880 --> 00:45:28.360
choices that people make.

00:45:28.360 --> 00:45:33.610
And I think if I look at the
choices that I have, I feel

00:45:33.610 --> 00:45:35.880
like I've a lot more choices
than the generation--

00:45:35.880 --> 00:45:37.400
that my mom's generation had.

00:45:37.400 --> 00:45:41.880
I have the ability to have this
amazing job, running an

00:45:41.880 --> 00:45:46.450
important part of Google's
business, and to have kids at

00:45:46.450 --> 00:45:47.150
the same time.

00:45:47.150 --> 00:45:49.520
And on the other hand, it's
not like there aren't

00:45:49.520 --> 00:45:49.850
trade-offs.

00:45:49.850 --> 00:45:52.090
It's not like there aren't some
compromises that I need

00:45:52.090 --> 00:45:53.930
to make on both sides.

00:45:53.930 --> 00:45:56.010
But I'm very fortunate
to live in this time.

00:45:56.010 --> 00:45:58.910
And I feel like the message that
I think is important to

00:45:58.910 --> 00:46:00.950
send to young girls is like
you have all these

00:46:00.950 --> 00:46:01.550
opportunities.

00:46:01.550 --> 00:46:03.500
You have choices.

00:46:03.500 --> 00:46:05.450
Those choices are yours.

00:46:05.450 --> 00:46:07.790
And there are trade-offs,
but there are choices.

00:46:07.790 --> 00:46:14.720
And I believe that women--

00:46:14.720 --> 00:46:17.210
that we have all these great
opportunities and that women

00:46:17.210 --> 00:46:18.700
should choose-- if
they choose--

00:46:18.700 --> 00:46:19.950
should take advantage of it.

00:46:26.895 --> 00:46:28.050
GAYATRI RAJAN: An average
man or a woman

00:46:28.050 --> 00:46:30.160
has 45 years of career--

00:46:30.160 --> 00:46:31.960
spanning about 45 years.

00:46:31.960 --> 00:46:34.690
Your children are going to be
with you 18 years maximum.

00:46:34.690 --> 00:46:36.540
And my kids are already
out the door.

00:46:36.540 --> 00:46:39.830
So I think that's something to
recognize that there will be

00:46:39.830 --> 00:46:45.150
periods of your time where you
invest a little bit more in

00:46:45.150 --> 00:46:47.880
work and other times where
you pull back and

00:46:47.880 --> 00:46:49.010
invest in your family.

00:46:49.010 --> 00:46:54.250
But recognizing that these
trade-offs will happen and

00:46:54.250 --> 00:46:56.540
recognizing that it's not
going to be the same

00:46:56.540 --> 00:46:59.320
trade-offs over your career
span, I think is very

00:46:59.320 --> 00:47:01.970
important for young
women to realize.

00:47:01.970 --> 00:47:02.630
It's a long-run game.

00:47:02.630 --> 00:47:04.030
It's a marathon.

00:47:04.030 --> 00:47:04.930
It's not a sprint.

00:47:04.930 --> 00:47:10.540
When you have your first baby,
it's not a five-year horizon

00:47:10.540 --> 00:47:14.180
that you're looking at in
investing for your career.

00:47:14.180 --> 00:47:15.620
MEGAN SMITH: I just tell people
when they come back

00:47:15.620 --> 00:47:16.750
from maternity leave,
right before--

00:47:16.750 --> 00:47:19.640
I'm like you know, you won't
realize, but somehow you won't

00:47:19.640 --> 00:47:21.260
actually get out the
door on time.

00:47:21.260 --> 00:47:24.080
And you'll need to change
your shirt three times.

00:47:24.080 --> 00:47:26.340
And you'll eventually
get here.

00:47:26.340 --> 00:47:28.980
But remember, babies are
only less than a

00:47:28.980 --> 00:47:30.230
year old for a year.

00:47:32.730 --> 00:47:36.040
So maybe you don't work as much
that year, as crazy like

00:47:36.040 --> 00:47:38.430
150% shipping and launching
and all that.

00:47:38.430 --> 00:47:40.690
And maybe you're in balance
with your team, and maybe

00:47:40.690 --> 00:47:42.300
you're not doing a
total start-up.

00:47:42.300 --> 00:47:44.530
But then you do a start-up when
they're a different age,

00:47:44.530 --> 00:47:47.070
so like that's a balance
for them.

00:47:47.070 --> 00:47:48.660
ANNA PATTERSON: And also
pregnancy gives you a really

00:47:48.660 --> 00:47:49.910
hard deadline.

00:47:53.350 --> 00:47:55.400
ANGELA LAI: A schedule
that doesn't slip.

00:47:55.400 --> 00:47:56.630
SUSAN WOJCICKI: I think the
other thing people forget,

00:47:56.630 --> 00:47:59.040
that if you work really hard and
you have a good job, you

00:47:59.040 --> 00:48:01.480
can hire people who
can help you.

00:48:01.480 --> 00:48:02.480
And they will help you.

00:48:02.480 --> 00:48:06.460
And you'll be able to help do
more to have more time,

00:48:06.460 --> 00:48:07.810
because you'll have help.

00:48:10.456 --> 00:48:12.980
MEGAN SMITH: Do you have women
in tech leaders that you guys

00:48:12.980 --> 00:48:14.240
look up to?

00:48:14.240 --> 00:48:16.964
Who and why?

00:48:16.964 --> 00:48:20.435
ANGELA LAI: I look
up to Susan.

00:48:20.435 --> 00:48:22.230
I worked with Susan
for a long time.

00:48:22.230 --> 00:48:23.280
A lot of us have.

00:48:23.280 --> 00:48:26.690
And I think that Adool it really
is one of the things

00:48:26.690 --> 00:48:29.105
that-- we've always had
people to look up to.

00:48:29.105 --> 00:48:31.610
And I typically sympathize
where you are in an

00:48:31.610 --> 00:48:33.700
organization where you're not.

00:48:33.700 --> 00:48:36.320
And I think that it
really does help.

00:48:36.320 --> 00:48:39.990
And I don't know how to bring
the Google culture to the rest

00:48:39.990 --> 00:48:41.070
of the world.

00:48:41.070 --> 00:48:43.680
We work really hard at it.

00:48:43.680 --> 00:48:47.610
We have also leaders like Alan
that I greatly admire as a

00:48:47.610 --> 00:48:50.310
"woman leader" because he really
does speak out for

00:48:50.310 --> 00:48:51.560
women a lot.

00:48:51.560 --> 00:48:55.450
And I think as a community, we
all need to encourage our

00:48:55.450 --> 00:48:57.350
leaders, also sometimes
a little bit shy

00:48:57.350 --> 00:48:58.050
about speaking up.

00:48:58.050 --> 00:49:00.120
But if you kick them,
they will do it.

00:49:00.120 --> 00:49:04.140
And then I think it's us all
encouraging each other.

00:49:04.140 --> 00:49:07.660
Just speak up for it, and I'll
champion for the NCWIT Sit

00:49:07.660 --> 00:49:11.090
With Me campaign again to
just try to strike the

00:49:11.090 --> 00:49:11.920
conversation.

00:49:11.920 --> 00:49:13.180
It doesn't have to
be controversial.

00:49:13.180 --> 00:49:15.660
It doesn't have to
be emotional.

00:49:15.660 --> 00:49:17.796
It's just talking to them.

00:49:17.796 --> 00:49:20.748
GAYATRI RAJAN: And I wanted
to say that--

00:49:20.748 --> 00:49:22.455
ANGELA LAI: Here,
I'll give you--

00:49:22.455 --> 00:49:25.230
GAYATRI RAJAN: I tend to look up
to people not when they've

00:49:25.230 --> 00:49:28.170
done something spectacular,
but when they've

00:49:28.170 --> 00:49:29.070
really given back.

00:49:29.070 --> 00:49:32.970
And I will say this, without
embarrassing

00:49:32.970 --> 00:49:35.170
Susan and even Angela--

00:49:35.170 --> 00:49:38.340
because I've worked with both
of them-- is they found ways

00:49:38.340 --> 00:49:41.840
to sponsor other people
in their org.

00:49:41.840 --> 00:49:46.870
Some of them women, sometimes
men, but I think they've

00:49:46.870 --> 00:49:51.270
invested and often not overtly,
it's often in ways

00:49:51.270 --> 00:49:55.410
that are behind closed doors,
or it's that little nudge.

00:49:55.410 --> 00:49:57.810
It's sponsoring you
in a meeting

00:49:57.810 --> 00:49:58.846
when you're not present.

00:49:58.846 --> 00:50:01.710
I think those are the kinds of
things they've done for the

00:50:01.710 --> 00:50:03.020
women in the org.

00:50:03.020 --> 00:50:05.670
And I know Angela has promoted
several women in her org.

00:50:05.670 --> 00:50:06.590
Susan has.

00:50:06.590 --> 00:50:12.050
And I'm a beneficiary of that.

00:50:12.050 --> 00:50:16.760
So I think it's great that we
have women at Google who do

00:50:16.760 --> 00:50:17.720
this for other women.

00:50:17.720 --> 00:50:21.470
And I feel this is one thing
that every woman, regardless

00:50:21.470 --> 00:50:23.560
of their level, this
is something we

00:50:23.560 --> 00:50:25.190
can do for each other.

00:50:25.190 --> 00:50:26.970
Women tend to--

00:50:26.970 --> 00:50:29.240
there's research that's found
that when women tend to ask

00:50:29.240 --> 00:50:34.820
for themselves, they are not
liked as much as when they ask

00:50:34.820 --> 00:50:37.100
for others, which is probably
why you all think that you're

00:50:37.100 --> 00:50:40.320
better at doing things on
behalf of others than

00:50:40.320 --> 00:50:43.090
yourself, because it's clearly
a feedback loop there.

00:50:43.090 --> 00:50:48.970
So if this is what we have to
deal with, then let's make the

00:50:48.970 --> 00:50:49.450
most of it.

00:50:49.450 --> 00:50:51.370
Let's try and help
other women.

00:50:51.370 --> 00:50:52.470
Sponsor someone.

00:50:52.470 --> 00:50:55.140
Say something nice about
someone when

00:50:55.140 --> 00:50:56.700
they're not in the room.

00:50:56.700 --> 00:51:00.560
Seed those thoughts in people.

00:51:00.560 --> 00:51:03.024
And I think that's a way we
can bring each other up.

00:51:03.024 --> 00:51:03.960
MEGAN SMITH: Terrific.

00:51:03.960 --> 00:51:05.110
Yeah, in the back of the room.

00:51:05.110 --> 00:51:08.490
AUDIENCE: Hi, I work here in
Silicon Valley, and frequently

00:51:08.490 --> 00:51:11.890
am the only woman in a room or
the only woman in a form.

00:51:11.890 --> 00:51:16.180
And I'm the community manager,
so spend a lot of time using

00:51:16.180 --> 00:51:18.820
your products, Google
products.

00:51:18.820 --> 00:51:22.290
And I wanted to thank you all
first for investing your time

00:51:22.290 --> 00:51:25.540
and effort to have this event
here, the pre-event

00:51:25.540 --> 00:51:27.700
dedicated to women.

00:51:27.700 --> 00:51:31.400
And I wanted to make a comment
and kind of also ask you for

00:51:31.400 --> 00:51:33.500
what your plans are in
the future, because I

00:51:33.500 --> 00:51:34.430
was all amped up.

00:51:34.430 --> 00:51:36.530
And it's like oh my
God, I quit--

00:51:36.530 --> 00:51:38.440
I stopped work--

00:51:38.440 --> 00:51:40.280
I had my last meeting.

00:51:40.280 --> 00:51:42.840
3 o'clock, hop in the
car, get over here.

00:51:42.840 --> 00:51:46.090
Check in at Google I/O. And
I'm ready to go here.

00:51:46.090 --> 00:51:47.760
And they give me a t-shirt.

00:51:47.760 --> 00:51:48.940
And it's size small--

00:51:48.940 --> 00:51:50.190
Men's.

00:51:52.570 --> 00:51:56.390
And I kind of thought maybe,
they didn't understand me,

00:51:56.390 --> 00:51:59.210
because when they asked
me to register they

00:51:59.210 --> 00:52:01.710
asked what my M-S--

00:52:01.710 --> 00:52:02.640
Ms., right?

00:52:02.640 --> 00:52:03.410
Female--

00:52:03.410 --> 00:52:04.870
and I got this invite,
so Google

00:52:04.870 --> 00:52:06.630
definitely knows I'm a woman.

00:52:06.630 --> 00:52:10.560
Are you guys sure that those
maybe green or gray ones don't

00:52:10.560 --> 00:52:12.250
come in women sizes?

00:52:12.250 --> 00:52:15.220
No, this is the smallest
you get.

00:52:15.220 --> 00:52:17.050
MEGAN SMITH: It's either
this or the XL.

00:52:19.730 --> 00:52:20.640
SUSAN WOJCICKI: It's funny.

00:52:20.640 --> 00:52:25.080
AUDIENCE: And then it's kind of
hard for-- and I'm not the

00:52:25.080 --> 00:52:27.140
kind of woman who's intimidated,
as you can tell.

00:52:27.140 --> 00:52:32.340
So that still makes
me feel unwelcome.

00:52:32.340 --> 00:52:34.480
And I don't want to make
this a big issue or

00:52:34.480 --> 00:52:35.390
confrontational thing.

00:52:35.390 --> 00:52:37.080
Because we're all women
and we don't do that.

00:52:40.810 --> 00:52:43.910
But the thing is I show up
and I want my shirt.

00:52:43.910 --> 00:52:47.385
And I don't want to be told
that I can sleep in it.

00:52:47.385 --> 00:52:50.820
So I would like to encourage
you, like, what are your plans

00:52:50.820 --> 00:52:51.520
for next I/O?

00:52:51.520 --> 00:52:54.150
How are you going to make women
who show up like me, and

00:52:54.150 --> 00:52:56.450
they're like, oh my God,
I'm so excited.

00:52:56.450 --> 00:52:59.380
And I don't care that I'm going
to be one, maybe, per

00:52:59.380 --> 00:53:02.900
100 attendees, just one
woman, but I'm here.

00:53:02.900 --> 00:53:05.460
How are you going to make it
even better next year?

00:53:05.460 --> 00:53:06.350
And thank you again.

00:53:06.350 --> 00:53:07.650
MEGAN SMITH: Sure.

00:53:07.650 --> 00:53:08.730
Thank you very much.

00:53:08.730 --> 00:53:13.830
You know, I love people
like you.

00:53:13.830 --> 00:53:16.670
When we see great ideas then
we can execute on them.

00:53:16.670 --> 00:53:20.295
So definitely let's work
on the t-shirts.

00:53:20.295 --> 00:53:21.520
That would be good.

00:53:21.520 --> 00:53:23.980
But I think, you know, Susan,
we had an event--

00:53:23.980 --> 00:53:24.530
what's that?

00:53:24.530 --> 00:53:25.770
AUDIENCE: Don't make
it pink yarn.

00:53:25.770 --> 00:53:28.220
MEGAN SMITH: No,
definitely not.

00:53:28.220 --> 00:53:31.186
I remember planning it out, we
had a rule, like, no rainbows.

00:53:31.186 --> 00:53:32.020
Oh, I'm sorry.

00:53:32.020 --> 00:53:35.440
That was the gay community
online in Web 1.0.

00:53:35.440 --> 00:53:36.430
Yes, no pink.

00:53:36.430 --> 00:53:38.520
Well, some pink for the
people who like pink.

00:53:38.520 --> 00:53:42.150
But Susan, we had an event
at Susan's house.

00:53:42.150 --> 00:53:45.890
We were lucky she hosted us and
you were talking about how

00:53:45.890 --> 00:53:48.830
it's important to have
gatherings where we come

00:53:48.830 --> 00:53:51.650
together, whether it was the
group when you had very few

00:53:51.650 --> 00:53:54.260
women-- like find other women
in the company somewhere and

00:53:54.260 --> 00:53:56.350
partner companies and just
build community.

00:53:56.350 --> 00:54:00.410
And so our hope is that this
event is the beginning of

00:54:00.410 --> 00:54:03.270
kicking that off and really
recognizing in a very public

00:54:03.270 --> 00:54:07.420
way, as part of the I/O agenda,
that we really as an

00:54:07.420 --> 00:54:10.720
industry need more women at
the table designing and

00:54:10.720 --> 00:54:11.730
building everything.

00:54:11.730 --> 00:54:14.160
And it's a really
important part--

00:54:14.160 --> 00:54:14.980
Susan, you've got something.

00:54:14.980 --> 00:54:16.220
SUSAN WOJCICKI: No, I was just
going to say I think it's

00:54:16.220 --> 00:54:17.000
great feedback.

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:21.270
And we'll communicate it.

00:54:21.270 --> 00:54:23.665
And next year, we'll have
women's t-shirts.

00:54:23.665 --> 00:54:24.060
MEGAN SMITH: Yay.

00:54:24.060 --> 00:54:24.520
AUDIENCE: [APPLAUSE]

00:54:24.520 --> 00:54:27.280
MEGAN SMITH: Definitely.

00:54:27.280 --> 00:54:29.900
So we mentioned Alan Eustace
because he's a big

00:54:29.900 --> 00:54:30.470
supporter of women.

00:54:30.470 --> 00:54:31.890
He mentioned--

00:54:31.890 --> 00:54:35.750
I was on stage with him and
he said I went to the--

00:54:35.750 --> 00:54:38.730
I think it was the Grace
Hopper conference.

00:54:38.730 --> 00:54:41.600
And he said I know what it felt
like, because I got a

00:54:41.600 --> 00:54:42.907
lipstick [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:45.889 --> 00:54:48.850
So I think that's the opposite
experience of

00:54:48.850 --> 00:54:50.360
what you just had.

00:54:50.360 --> 00:54:51.240
MEGAN SMITH: That's
really good.

00:54:51.240 --> 00:54:54.380
And you know, we talked about
Alan, but also credit to Larry

00:54:54.380 --> 00:54:59.160
and Sergey, they've always been
really just open-minded

00:54:59.160 --> 00:55:02.870
about talent inclusion, which
is the way I think of

00:55:02.870 --> 00:55:07.510
diversity and just the way we
work, not only inventing

00:55:07.510 --> 00:55:09.910
products but also how our
company should be.

00:55:09.910 --> 00:55:12.870
And early on, I was not there
for this, but Marissa tells

00:55:12.870 --> 00:55:17.790
the story of Larry getting yet
another guy's resume for

00:55:17.790 --> 00:55:20.520
engineering across his
desk to improve.

00:55:20.520 --> 00:55:24.100
And he just said OK, you get a
couple more of these, but if

00:55:24.100 --> 00:55:27.590
there are no women in the queue,
there's no more hiring.

00:55:27.590 --> 00:55:31.390
And so to take that kind of
leadership as the CEO at the

00:55:31.390 --> 00:55:33.900
time was really a significant
move.

00:55:33.900 --> 00:55:34.850
And it sets the tone.

00:55:34.850 --> 00:55:38.640
They always wear the Women at
Google shirts and the Gaygler

00:55:38.640 --> 00:55:39.160
shirts, whatever.

00:55:39.160 --> 00:55:41.410
They're really sort of trying
to re-represent the company

00:55:41.410 --> 00:55:42.810
back to us.

00:55:42.810 --> 00:55:46.330
And so that's another, I guess,
action item, I'd say is

00:55:46.330 --> 00:55:49.500
that ask your leaders
to team up with you.

00:55:49.500 --> 00:55:52.340
And maybe if you need to give
them some of these examples,

00:55:52.340 --> 00:55:53.370
but they're there.

00:55:53.370 --> 00:55:55.740
So I think we're at time.

00:55:55.740 --> 00:55:56.925
AUDIENCE: One question?

00:55:56.925 --> 00:55:57.800
MEGAN SMITH: Oh, one
more question, OK.

00:55:57.800 --> 00:55:59.210
AUDIENCE: It's a
quick question.

00:55:59.210 --> 00:56:01.120
I'm a software engineer.

00:56:01.120 --> 00:56:02.980
And I interviewed at Google.

00:56:02.980 --> 00:56:04.800
And I was interviewed
by all men.

00:56:04.800 --> 00:56:07.240
And I thought it would have
been advantageous for both

00:56:07.240 --> 00:56:10.390
sides to have at least one
woman interview me.

00:56:10.390 --> 00:56:12.100
And I was wondering what your
thoughts are on that.

00:56:16.750 --> 00:56:17.820
ANNA PATTERSON: We
try really hard.

00:56:17.820 --> 00:56:20.310
We used to have the rule, a hard
and fast rule that that

00:56:20.310 --> 00:56:21.510
had to happen.

00:56:21.510 --> 00:56:24.790
And as the company--

00:56:24.790 --> 00:56:26.680
we have different times
where we have

00:56:26.680 --> 00:56:28.680
very fast hiring velocity.

00:56:28.680 --> 00:56:33.160
And so in one of those times,
it's relaxed a little bit.

00:56:33.160 --> 00:56:36.136
But it's usually a hard
and fast rule.

00:56:36.136 --> 00:56:36.800
MEGAN SMITH: It's important.

00:56:36.800 --> 00:56:38.940
Important point.

00:56:38.940 --> 00:56:41.210
I guess we'll close with
something exciting that I

00:56:41.210 --> 00:56:42.560
learned recently.

00:56:42.560 --> 00:56:45.860
Walter Isaacson, of course,
wrote the amazing book about

00:56:45.860 --> 00:56:48.180
Steve Jobs' biography.

00:56:48.180 --> 00:56:51.490
And I recently read that
he's working on a

00:56:51.490 --> 00:56:54.130
biography of Ada Lovelace.

00:56:54.130 --> 00:56:57.730
And he's doing this because he
became aware of her from his

00:56:57.730 --> 00:57:00.100
daughter who's 21
and I think just

00:57:00.100 --> 00:57:01.610
finishing in computer science.

00:57:01.610 --> 00:57:04.900
And I had never heard of her
until I went to Silicon Valley

00:57:04.900 --> 00:57:06.460
Comes to the UK.

00:57:06.460 --> 00:57:07.955
And there's actually
a portrait of her

00:57:07.955 --> 00:57:09.000
at 10 Downing Street.

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:12.550
We were lucky to be there for an
app-a-thon contest judging.

00:57:12.550 --> 00:57:13.860
And there she was.

00:57:13.860 --> 00:57:17.960
And for those who don't know
her, she was teamed up with

00:57:17.960 --> 00:57:20.330
Babbage on the Babbage engine.

00:57:20.330 --> 00:57:22.610
And she was really the
first person--

00:57:22.610 --> 00:57:25.670
not woman, not man-- first
person to come up with the

00:57:25.670 --> 00:57:28.470
idea of sort of symbolics,
and the idea of what is

00:57:28.470 --> 00:57:28.740
programming.

00:57:28.740 --> 00:57:33.360
It was a mechanical computer at
the time, but really, kind

00:57:33.360 --> 00:57:35.660
of really the world's
first programmer

00:57:35.660 --> 00:57:38.140
for symbolics thinker.

00:57:38.140 --> 00:57:42.800
So pretty exciting to see kind
of our history begin to come

00:57:42.800 --> 00:57:44.555
back at us in that way.

00:57:44.555 --> 00:57:46.550
So I'm looking forward to
reading that book and learning

00:57:46.550 --> 00:57:48.990
